article.description:
The Bulls, missing two injured starters, overcame an ugly first
half to beat Atlanta 96-90 Wednesday night, completing a three-game sweep of the Hawks.
article.headline: Bulls rally to beat Hawks, hang onto 8th in East
article.linkText: Bulls rally to beat Hawks, hang onto 8th in East
article.story:
ATLANTA (AP) -- The Chicago Bulls can control their playoff hopes, though no one knows how many healthy players they will have left if they make it to the postseason. The Bulls, missing two injured starters, overcame an ugly first half to beat Atlanta 96-90 Wednesday night and maintain their eighth-place tie in the playoff standings. Ben Gordon led the Bulls with 19 points despite battling a sprained left ankle. Chicago's other starting guard, Kirk Hinrich, had to have a dislocated finger popped into place during the game. The Bulls were without guard Chris Duhon (lower back pain) for the second straight game and forward Luol Deng (concussion) for the third straight. When a reporter referred to Gordon's injury as little after the game, Gordon said, "It's not little. It's bad." Still, Gordon played almost 43 minutes. With Chicago in a tight playoff race, this was no time to sit. "It was a tough it out game," said Hinrich, who played 39 minutes and had X-rays on his hand after the game. "It's just my pinky finger, so it's not that big a deal," Hinrich said. The Bulls remained tied for eighth place in the Eastern Conference with the Philadelphia 76ers, who beat New Jersey on Wednesday night. Chicago owns the tiebreaker with Philadelphia due to a better conference record. "We're not taking a breath," Gordon said. "Philly just won tonight. We've got to stay focused and continue to win the games." After trailing by 10 points entering the second period and shooting only 32 percent from the field in the first half, the Bulls recovered with a strong third quarter to complete a three-game sweep of the Hawks. Hinrich had 17 points and seven assists, and Michael Sweetney added 15 points. Malik Allen, 0-for-7 from the field through three quarters, had nine points in the final period. The Bulls arrived in Atlanta late Tuesday night after a win over New Jersey. "We were very, very fortunate," Bulls coach Scott Skiles said. "Clearly, we were tired right from the beginning of the game. It wasn't a pretty game. We just played hard in the second half and really battled for it." Josh Smith led the Hawks with 22 points. Tyronn Lue had 15 points and Joe Johnson had 14 points and eight assists. Atlanta's Josh Childress was ejected with 2:33 left in the game for a flagrant foul against Chicago's Andres Nocioni. Replays showed Childress was hit in the throat by Nocioni's elbow and Childress responded by hitting Nocioni in the back of the head. "The game got physical and kind of got out of hand," Childress said, adding the officials "let it get out of hand." Chicago's Tyson Chandler and Atlanta's Zaza Pachulia were called for technical fouls after tempers flared in a battle for a loose ball early in the fourth quarter. "I was just trying to protect my teammates," Chandler said. "(The Hawks) wanted to win. It's all in the game. I don't think anyone was out there taking any cheap shots. ... Both teams were diving for loose balls and both teams wanted it." Said Smith, also called for a technical foul in the fourth quarter: "I like it like that. We played hard. We're not going to back down from anybody. ... Anything a team can do, we can dish it right back." The Hawks were without forward Al Harrington due to a bruised left hand. Both teams struggled with poor shooting in the first half. Smith rejected six shots in the first half, contributing to the Bulls' 33 percent shooting. Chicago trailed most of the half but was tied 43-all at halftime. Nocioni made only two of 12 shots in the first half and had several of his inside attempts rejected by Smith. But Nocioni, who had 14 points, hit a 3-pointer early in the third period, and Hinrich had nine points in the period. After a 53-all tie, the Bulls outscored the Hawks 17-6 the rest of the period to take a 70-60 lead into the final period. Game notes
Rookie F Marvin Williams started for Harrington and had 10 points. ... The Bulls, who swept last season's four-game series with the Hawks, have won seven straight in the series. ... Nocioni had 11 rebounds. ... Pachulia had 12 points and 10 rebounds.
